===Activation semantics===

Upon activation at height H:

* <code>OP_NOP4</code> (<code>0xB3</code>) is enforced as <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> in all Tapscript executions.
* Transactions containing <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> with invalid SPHINCS+ signatures are consensus-invalid in blocks at height H and above.
* Annex format rules for SPHINCS+ signatures (type byte <code>0x04</code>, strict parsing) are enforced.
* The <code>SCRIPT_VERIFY_DISCOURAGE_UPGRADABLE_NOPS</code> policy flag no longer rejects <code>OP_NOP4</code> in the mempool (it is now a defined opcode).

Key-path spending modifications (internal key disclosure, NUMS point ban, bare-key grace period and rate limiting) are specified in [[bip-0368.mediawiki|BIP 368]] and may be activated simultaneously.

===Pre-activation considerations===

Because <code>OP_NOP4</code> is valid in Tapscript today, users may begin creating Taproot outputs with SPHINCS+ tapleaves before activation (see ''Pre-activation usage'' under Design). These outputs are fully spendable via other tapleaves or key-path on the current network. The SPHINCS+ tapleaf becomes enforceable only after activation.

This property makes BIP 369 uniquely suited to proactive quantum risk mitigation: users can secure funds today against a future quantum threat without waiting for the soft fork to activate.

==Resource Limits==

<code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> interacts with the [[bip-0342.mediawiki|BIP 342]] per-script validation weight budget as follows:

===Validation weight budget===

The budget is initialized as <code>witness_serialized_size + VALIDATION_WEIGHT_OFFSET</code> (where <code>VALIDATION_WEIGHT_OFFSET = 50</code>). Each successful <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> deducts <code>VALIDATION_WEIGHT_PER_SPHINCS_SIGOP</code> from the budget. If the budget goes negative, the script fails with <code>TAPSCRIPT_VALIDATION_WEIGHT</code>.

The value of <code>VALIDATION_WEIGHT_PER_SPHINCS_SIGOP</code> must reflect the actual CPU cost of SPHINCS+ verification relative to witness weight. SPHINCS+ verification involves thousands of SHA-256 evaluations and is significantly more expensive than Schnorr verification. The production value will be determined by benchmarking; the reference implementation uses a placeholder value pending measurement.

===Annex and stack size limits===

SPHINCS+ signatures (4080 bytes each) are carried in the annex, not on the script stack. They are therefore '''not''' subject to the 520-byte <code>MAX_SCRIPT_ELEMENT_SIZE</code> limit that applies to stack elements. The annex contributes to witness weight but has no independent consensus size limit beyond the overall block weight constraint.

===Maximum signatures per transaction===

Each SPHINCS+ signature adds approximately 4080 bytes to the witness, contributing approximately 1020 weight units (under the segwit 4:1 witness discount). The maximum block weight is 4,000,000 WU. In practice, a single transaction can contain several SPHINCS+ signatures; the limiting factor is the validation weight budget rather than block weight.

For a transaction with a single SPHINCS+ signature: the witness is approximately 4080 (sig) + 100 (script + control block + overhead) = 4180 bytes. The validation weight budget is approximately 4230, which comfortably accommodates the sigop cost.

==Security Considerations==

===Annex malleability===

In hybrid scripts, the Schnorr signature is computed over the standard [[bip-0342.mediawiki|BIP 342]] sighash which includes <code>sha_annex</code>. This commits to the exact annex contents. Any modification to the annex (including the SPHINCS+ signatures it carries) would invalidate the Schnorr signature, preventing third-party malleability.

In SPHINCS+-only scripts (no Schnorr signature), annex malleability is prevented by strict annex parsing: the annex must be exactly <code>0x50 || 0x04 || compact_size(N) || N * 4080 bytes</code> with no trailing data, and all N signatures must be consumed by script execution. There is no room for a malleator to inject or modify data.

===Signing order===

The signing order (SPHINCS+ first, then Schnorr) is a normative requirement. Constructing signatures in the wrong order will produce invalid transactions because the Schnorr sighash depends on <code>sha_annex</code>, which cannot be computed until the SPHINCS+ signatures are known. Wallet implementations must enforce this ordering.

===Circular sighash dependency===

The SPHINCS+ sighash intentionally omits <code>sha_annex</code> to break the circular dependency that would otherwise exist: a signature stored in the annex cannot be computed over a message that includes a hash of itself. The annex-present bit in <code>spend_type</code> remains set to 1 for domain separation, ensuring the SPHINCS+ sighash is distinct from a non-annex Tapscript sighash.

===Hybrid security model===

The hybrid model provides defense in depth: if Schnorr signatures are broken by a quantum adversary, the SPHINCS+ check (enforced on upgraded nodes) prevents unauthorized spending. If the SPHINCS+ scheme is broken, the Schnorr check (enforced on all nodes) prevents unauthorized spending. An attacker must break both simultaneously.

This protection fully applies only after a sufficient portion of the network has upgraded and activated the soft fork. Before activation, non-upgraded nodes enforce only the Schnorr check. This is the same trust model as all prior soft forks: security during transition relies on economic majority enforcement.

===Annex cursor and conditional branches===

The annex cursor advances only on ''executed'' <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> opcodes. Opcodes inside unexecuted <code>OP_IF</code>/<code>OP_ELSE</code> branches do not advance the cursor. Script authors must ensure that the annex is constructed with the correct number of signatures for the execution path that will be taken. All annex signatures must be consumed by the end of execution; unconsumed signatures cause script failure.

===Transaction weight===

Each SPHINCS+ signature adds 4080 bytes to the witness (1020 weight units under the segwit witness discount). A single-signature hybrid transaction adds approximately 4 KB to the witness. Multi-signature constructions via MAST tapleaves add weight proportional to the number of required signers in the chosen tapleaf (k), not the total number of possible signers (n).

===Batch verification===

SPHINCS+ verification involves thousands of hash evaluations per signature and is significantly more expensive than Schnorr verification. Implementations may batch hash computations across multiple SPHINCS+ signatures within the same transaction or block to amortize overhead. However, batch verification must produce the same pass/fail result as individual verification for each signature; batch-specific optimizations must not weaken consensus guarantees.

===Key-path spending and quantum risk===

This BIP does not modify Taproot key-path spending rules. A quantum adversary capable of solving the elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem (ECDLP) can forge Schnorr signatures and key-path spend any witness version 1 output, regardless of whether a SPHINCS+ tapleaf exists in the MAST tree.

To mitigate this risk:

* Users seeking quantum insurance should use a NUMS internal key (see ''Recommended wallet constructions''), which makes key-path spending impossible by construction. Upon activation of [[bip-0368.mediawiki|BIP 368]] (companion proposal), key-path spending with the NUMS point is also banned at the consensus level.
* [[bip-0368.mediawiki|BIP 368]] specifies key-path witness augmentation (internal key disclosure via annex), NUMS point ban, and bare-key output protection (grace period + rate limiting). It may be activated simultaneously with this BIP for comprehensive post-quantum defense.

===Unknown public key types===

If the top stack element is not exactly 32 bytes, <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> treats it as an unknown key type: the annex cursor advances (consuming a signature slot) but no verification is performed. This preserves soft-fork extensibility for future post-quantum schemes with different key sizes, following the same forward-compatibility pattern as [[bip-0342.mediawiki|BIP 342]] Schnorr key versioning.

==Test Vectors==

Test vectors are provided in [[bip-0369-test-vectors.json]] and include:

* '''Keypair:''' Deterministic key generation from 16-byte seeds, producing a 64-byte secret key and 32-byte public key.
* '''SPHINCS+ sighash:''' Complete sighash preimage showing all fields, demonstrating that <code>sha_annex</code> is omitted while <code>spend_type</code> retains the annex bit (0x03).
* '''Signature:''' A valid 4080-byte SLH-DSA signature over the sighash.
* '''SPHINCS+-only transaction:''' Complete serialized witness for a script-path spend using only <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code>.
* '''Hybrid transaction:''' Complete serialized witness for a Schnorr + SPHINCS+ hybrid spend, demonstrating the signing order (SPHINCS+ first, then Schnorr) and that the Schnorr sighash includes <code>sha_annex</code>.
* '''Invalid signature:''' A corrupted signature (first byte flipped) that must fail verification.
* '''Annex format:''' Encoding examples showing the <code>0x50 || 0x04 || compact_size(N) || sig</code> structure.

==Reference Implementation==

A reference implementation is provided on the Bitcoin Core branch accompanying this BIP. It vendors [https://github.com/pq-code-package/slhdsa-c slhdsa-c] (Apache-2.0 / ISC / MIT triple license) into <code>src/crypto/sphincsplus/</code> and defines the custom Bitcoin parameter set (<code>slh_dsa_bitcoin</code>) using standard FIPS 205 algorithms with the tree parameters specified above.

The implementation includes:
* <code>OP_CHECKSPHINCSVERIFY</code> opcode handler in the script interpreter
* Annex parsing and signature cursor management
* <code>SignatureHashSphincs</code> (BIP 342 sighash minus sha_annex)
* <code>VerifySphincsSignature</code> wrapper for consensus verification
* Functional tests covering hybrid scripts, SPHINCS+-only scripts, error cases, and multi-signature scenarios
* Buried deployment activation via <code>-testactivationheight=sphincs@N</code>

==Addendum: Design Rationale for Standard SLH-DSA Algorithms==

===Why standard WOTS+ and FORS instead of W+C_P+FP===

The tree parameters in this BIP (n=16, h=32, d=4, w=256, k=10, a=14) are drawn from "Hash-based Signature Schemes for Bitcoin" (Kudinov and Nick, [https://eprint.iacr.org/2025/2203 ePrint 2025/2203]). That paper also proposes two algorithm-level optimizations that reduce signature size:

* '''WOTS+C''' (Constant-sum WOTS+): eliminates 2 checksum chains per WOTS+ signature by grinding a counter until message digest digits sum to a fixed target. Reduces WOTS+ chains from 18 to 16. See [https://eprint.iacr.org/2022/778 ePrint 2022/778].
* '''PORS+FP''' (PORS with Fixed Points): replaces k independent FORS trees with a single tree and compact "Octopus" authentication sets. Reduces FORS proof size significantly.

Together, these optimizations would reduce the signature size from 4080 bytes to approximately 3408 bytes.

This BIP uses the '''standard''' FIPS 205 algorithms (WOTS+ with checksum chains, FORS with independent trees) for the following reasons:

====NIST-standardized and well-analyzed====

Standard WOTS+ and FORS are part of FIPS 205, which has undergone extensive public review through the NIST Post-Quantum Cryptography standardization process (2016-2024). The W+C_P+FP optimizations are newer (2022/2025) and have not been through comparable review.

====Same security level====

Both variants target NIST Security Category 1 (128-bit classical / ~64-bit quantum). The standard algorithms are marginally more conservative: WOTS+ checksum chains provide a structural integrity guarantee, and FORS independent trees have simpler security proofs than the Octopus construction.

====Drop-in upgrade path====

The W+C_P+FP variant uses the same hypertree structure (h=32, d=4, h'=8) and the same hash function (SHA-256 truncated to 16 bytes). A future upgrade to the optimized variant would only change the WOTS and FORS internals, not the hypertree traversal, sighash computation, or consensus rules. The upgrade would be a soft fork that tightens the accepted signature size from 4080 to 3408 bytes.

===Signature size comparison===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Component !! Standard (this BIP) !! W+C_P+FP (future optimization)
|-
| Randomizer R || 16 || 16
|-
| FORS / PORS proof || 2400 (k x (a+1) x n) || ~1660 (Octopus auth set)
|-
| WOTS+ signatures || 1152 (d x 18 x n) || 1024 (d x 16 x n) + 16 (counters)
|-
| Auth paths || 512 (d x h' x n) || 512
|-
| '''Total''' || '''4080 bytes''' || '''~3408 bytes'''
|}

The 672-byte difference (16% reduction) is meaningful for transaction weight but does not affect security, consensus rules, or the hybrid deployment model.
